Cumulative-Stiffness Transport and a Covariant Toy Model for Curvature–Memory Loading


Theorem (Marginal Accumulation of the Cumulative Coordinate)

Consider a cumulative response system in which the loading density obeys a p-Laplacian transport functional such that

    m(r) = |∇S| ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/(p-1)).

Assume outer-galaxy asymptotics

    g_b(r) ~ GM_b / r^2
    g_obs(r) ~ V_∞^2 / r.

Define the cumulative stiffness coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds.

Then u(r) grows logarithmically in the outer galaxy if and only if

    p = 4.


Proof

Under the assumed asymptotics

    g_b g_obs ~ r^(-3).

Hence

    m(r) ~ r^(-3/(p-1)).

Therefore

    u(r) ~ ∫^r s^(-3/(p-1)) ds.

The integral becomes logarithmic exactly when

    3/(p-1) = 1

which implies

    p = 4.

For p < 4 the cumulative integral converges, while for p > 4 it grows as a power law.

Thus p = 4 is the unique marginal accumulation case. ∎



X. Minimal Covariant Toy Model

We now construct a minimal covariant dynamical model whose weak-field limit reproduces the empirically preferred galaxy loading law

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/3)

together with the cumulative response structure

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds
    dS/du ≈ const.

The goal is not a full relativistic completion but a minimal dynamical embedding of the phenomenology.



X.1 Curvature–Memory Field

Introduce a scalar memory field

    M(x)

representing the local amplitude of retained geometric loading.

In the galaxy weak-field regime

    m(r) ~ M(r).



X.2 Source–Response Overlap Invariant

Memory loading is assumed to depend on the overlap between sourced curvature and realised curvature.

Define a scalar invariant

    Π(x)

satisfying the weak-field condition

    Π → g_b g_obs.



X.3 Covariant Lagrangian

The minimal toy Lagrangian is

    L =
    √(-g) [
        1/2 ∇_μ M ∇^μ M
        − a/4 M^4
        + b Π M
    ].

Terms

    kinetic     → transport of memory
    quartic     → nonlinear self-energy
    source      → curvature-overlap forcing



X.4 Field Equation

Variation gives

    □M + a M^3 = b Π

where

    □ = ∇_μ ∇^μ.



X.5 Weak-Field Constitutive Balance

In quasi-static galaxies

    □M << a M^3

so

    a M^3 ≈ b Π.

Hence

    M ∝ Π^(1/3).

Using the weak-field reduction

    Π → g_b g_obs

we obtain

    M ∝ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3).



X.6 Cumulative Stiffness Coordinate

Define

    u(r) = ∫_0^r M(s) ds.

Empirically

    dS/du ≈ σ₀

so

    S = σ₀ u.

Normalising at the turnover radius R_s

    S = u / u(R_s).

The velocity relation becomes

    V / V_∞ = 1 − exp[ −u(r) / u(R_s) ].



X.7 Outer Galaxy Behaviour

Outer asymptotics give

    g_b g_obs ~ r^(-3).

Thus

    M(r) ~ r^(-1)

and

    u(r) ~ ln r.

This reproduces the marginal accumulation predicted by the theorem.



X.8 Covariant Construction of the Overlap Invariant

Define the four-acceleration of static observers

    a_μ = u^ν ∇_ν u_μ.

In the weak-field limit

    (a_μ a^μ)^(1/2) → g_obs.

Define a baryonic potential

    ∇² Φ_b = 4π G ρ_b.

Then

    |∇Φ_b| → g_b.

The simplest scalar overlap invariant is

    Π =
        sqrt[
            (∇_μ Φ_b ∇^μ Φ_b)
            (a_ν a^ν)
        ].

Thus

    Π → g_b g_obs.



X.9 Weak-Field Radial Equation

In spherical symmetry the field equation reduces to

    (1/r²) (r² M')'
    + a M³
    = b g_b(r) g_obs(r).

This is a nonlinear reaction–diffusion equation.

term                meaning
diffusion           transport of memory
reaction            nonlinear constitutive response
source              baryonic–response overlap



X.10 Dimensionless Form

Let

    x = r / R_s
    M = M_s y(x).

Then

    ε (1/x²)(x² y')' + y³ = Γ(x)

where

    ε = 1 / (a M_s² R_s²)
    Γ(x) = (b / (a M_s³)) g_b g_obs.



X.11 Local Constitutive Regime

For

    ε << 1

the diffusion term is negligible and

    y³ = Γ(x)

so

    M ∝ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3).



X.12 Radial Acceleration Relation (RAR)

The acceleration is

    g_obs =
        V_∞² / r
        (1 − e^(−S))².

For weak response

    S << 1

we obtain

    g_obs ≈
        V_∞² / r
        (u(r) / u(R_s))².

With

    u'(r) ~ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3)

the theory predicts a nonlocal RAR.



X.13 Local Power-Law Approximation

Assume locally

    g_b(r) ~ r^(−q).

Then the predicted RAR slope becomes

    β_RAR = 2 − 3/q.

Examples

    baryonic falloff      predicted slope

    q = 2                 g_obs ~ g_b^(1/2)
    q ≈ 1.9               slope ≈ 0.42



